    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="488"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d488">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.111Mexico/203: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Ciudad Juarez</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dye</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">El Paso, Tex</hi>
                        </placeName>., <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-29">April 29,
                            1929</date>.<lb/>[Received 3:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A number of Mexican rebel civilians who were granted asylum in the United States
                    now desire to obtain immigration visas to regularize their entry for permanent
                    stay but dare not cross to this side to obtain visas at consulate. Under these
                    unusual circumstances does Department <pb facs="0525" n="407" xml:id="pg_407"/>
                    approve of some one from this Consulate taking such applications at the United
                    States immigration station at the boundary?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dye</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
